Azure Storage Account Creation & Blob Operations Using Azure CLI

1. Azure CLI Installation & Setup : 
Description:
 Installed Azure CLI on the local machine to interact with Azure cloud services using command-line interface.
Steps Performed:
Installed Azure CLI using Winget package manager
Verified installation using version command
Restarted terminal to apply environment changes
Commands Used:
winget install -e --id Microsoft.AzureCLI


az version
Outcome:
 Azure CLI successfully installed and verified, enabling cloud resource management from terminal.








2. Azure Account Login & Subscription Verification
Description:
 Authenticated into Azure account and verified active subscription.
Steps Performed:
Logged into Azure account using browser authentication
Verified active subscription details
Listed available subscriptions
Commands Used:
az login


az account show

az account list --output table
Outcome:
 Successfully authenticated and confirmed correct Azure subscription for deployment.




3. Resource Group Creation
Description:
 Created a logical container (Resource Group) to organize all Azure resources.
Azure Resource Group
Steps Performed:
Defined resource group name and region
Created resource group in Azure
Commands Used:
az group create --name rg-storage-demo --location eastus
Outcome:
 Resource group successfully created to manage all storage-related resources.







4. Storage Account Creation
Description:
 Created a Storage Account to store unstructured data like blobs.
Azure Storage Account
Steps Performed:
Generated unique storage account name
Created storage account with Standard_LRS replication
Enabled StorageV2 (general-purpose v2 account)
Commands Used:
az storage account create `
 --name storagedemo1234 `
 --resource-group rg-storage-demo `
 --location eastus `
 --sku Standard_LRS `
 --kind StorageV2
Outcome:
 Storage account successfully created for blob data operations.





5. Blob Container Creation
Description:
 Created a private blob container to store uploaded files.
Azure Blob Storage
Steps Performed:
Retrieved storage account access key
Created container with private access level
Commands Used:
az storage container create `
  --name $containerName `
  --account-name $storageAccount `
  --account-key $storageKey `
  --public-access off

Outcome:
 Blob container successfully created to store uploaded files securely.


6. Local File Creation
Description:
 Created two text files locally using PowerShell for upload to Azure Blob Storage.
Steps Performed:
Created working directory on local machine
Generated two text files with sample content
Commands Used:
mkdir C:\Users\DELL\Downloads\RealityworksAI\azure-downloads -Force

Set-Content "C:\azure-files\file1.txt" "Hello Azure File 1"
Set-Content "C:\azure-files\file2.txt" "Hello Azure File 2"
Outcome:
 Two local text files created successfully for cloud upload.




7. Upload Files to Azure Blob Storage
Description:
 Uploaded local files to Azure Blob Storage container.
Azure Blob Storage
Steps Performed:
Uploaded file1.txt to blob container
Uploaded file2.txt to blob container
Used storage account key authentication
Commands Used:
az storage blob upload `
  --account-name $storageAccount `
  --account-key $storageKey `
  --container-name $containerName `
  --file "C:\Users\DELL\Downloads\RealityworksAI\azure-files\file1.txt" `
  --name "file1.txt"






az storage blob upload `
  --account-name $storageAccount `
  --account-key $storageKey `
  --container-name $containerName `
  --file "C:\Users\DELL\Downloads\RealityworksAI\azure-files\file2.txt" `
  --name "file2.txt"

Outcome:
 Files successfully uploaded and stored in Azure Blob Storage.


8. File Modification & Overwrite
Description:
 Updated local files and re-uploaded them to Azure Blob Storage, overwriting existing blobs.
Steps Performed:
Modified content of local text files
Re-uploaded files using same blob names
Enabled overwrite option
Commands Used:
notepad C:\Users\DELL\Downloads\RealityworksAI\azure-downloads\file1.txt

notepad C:\Users\DELL\Downloads\RealityworksAI\azure-downloads\file2.txt

After the File Editing process UPload the latest changes in the Blob Storage : 

az storage blob upload `
  --account-name $storageAccount `
  --account-key $storageKey `
  --container-name $containerName `
  --file "C:\Users\DELL\Downloads\RealityworksAI\azure-downloads\file1.txt" `
  --name "file1.txt" `
  --overwrite true


Outcome:
 Existing blobs were successfully overwritten with updated file content.



9. Download Files from Azure Blob Storage
Description:
 Downloaded files from Azure Blob Storage to local machine.
Azure Blob Storage
Steps Performed:
Created local download directory
Downloaded blobs from container
Verified downloaded files
Commands Used:
mkdir C:\azure-downloads

az storage blob download `
  --account-name $storageAccount `
  --account-key $storageKey `
  --container-name $containerName `
  --name "file1.txt" `
  --file "C:\Users\DELL\Downloads\RealityworksAI\azure-downloads\file1.txt"


az storage blob download `
  --account-name $storageAccount `
  --account-key $storageKey `
  --container-name $containerName `
  --name "file2.txt" `
  --file "C:\Users\DELL\Downloads\RealityworksAI\azure-downloads\file2.txt"


Outcome:
 Files successfully downloaded and verified locally from Azure.



